{{About|German environmental organization||Robin Wood (disambiguation)}} {{Infobox organization | name = Robin Wood | logo = | type = [[Non-governmental organization]] | founded_date = 12 November 1982 | location = [[Bremen]], [[Germany]] | key_people = Florian Kubitz (CEO) | area_served = Germany | focus = [[Environmentalism]] | method = [[Direct action]] | revenue = [[Euro|€]]900,000 (2004) | num_members = 1400 | homepage = http://www.robinwood.de }}
'''Robin Wood''' is a [[Germany|German]] [[Environmental movement|environmental advocacy]] group. The group was founded in 1982 by former members of [[Greenpeace]] who desired a decentralized [[grassroots]] organization with greater autonomy to address specific local German issues.<ref>{{cite book | first=Neil | last=Carter | title=The Politics of the Environment: Ideas, Activism, Policy | page=155 | publisher=Cambridge University Press | edition=2 |date=May 2007 | ISBN=0-521-86802-5}}</ref> Robin Wood is based in [[Bremen]] and, in 2008, was composed of fifteen mostly autonomous regional groups within Germany.<ref>{{cite news | first=Sonia | last=Gigler | title= Robin Wood: Germany's Bare Branch Avenger | url=http://www.cafebabel.co.uk/article/24137/robin-wood-germanys-bare-branch-avenger.html | newspaper=Cafe Babel | date=11 March 2008 | accessdate=2011-04-27}}</ref>
Initially concerned with the [[Conservation (ethic)|conservation]] of German forests, particularly the [[Black Forest]],<ref>{{cite book | first1=John | last1=Barry | first2=E. Gene | last2=Frankland | publisher=Routledge |date=December 2001 | ISBN= 0-415-20285-X | title=International encyclopedia of environmental politics | page=47 }}</ref> the group's activism efforts later expanded to include rainforest conservation, [[paper recycling]], reduction of [[acid rain]] and other related areas. Robin Wood stages "attention-grabbing" demonstrations and confrontational public protests to raise awareness.<ref name="Markham">{{cite book | first=William T. | last=Markham | title=Environmental Organizations in Modern Germany: Hardy Survivors in the Twentieth Century and Beyond | pages=203–204 | publisher=Berghahn Books |date=August 2008 | ISBN=1-84545-447-2}}</ref> Although peaceful, the demonstrations are described as "often illegal."<ref name="Markham"/> The group publishes the quarterly ''Robin Wood Magazin''.
